      <body>
         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne Botanic Garden, ¶ 1 September 1872. ¶  ¶ Since I wrote last, noble friend, Colonel Warburton has suddenly appeared on the scene to lead an exploring expedition from Central Mount Stuart ¶ On...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="de">72.09.01</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="de">To August Petermann</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="de">
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">Sammlung Perthes Archiv,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               </seg>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">SPA ARCH<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               </seg>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">PGM<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               </seg>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">328</seg>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               </seg>Forschungsbibliothek Gotha der Universität Erfurt.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; "/>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="de">
               <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn0" n="1">
                  <p rend="FootnoteText"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>MS annotation by Petermann: 'Erh. 28. Okt. 1872' [Received 28 October 1872]. A partial, lightly-edited version of this letter was published by Petermann, see B73.03.09. For a published version of the full letter, see Voigt (1996), pp. 111-2.</p>
               </note>Melbourne, im bot. Garten,</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="de">1/9/72</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="de">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Seit ich zuletzt schrieb, edler Freund, ist plötzlich Oberst Warburton aufgetreten, um eine Forschungsreise von Central Berg Stuart nach dem Schwanfluss zu übernehmen u zwar auf Antrieb und mit Unterstützung meines Freundes, des Senators Mr Th Elder. Ja ich glaube, dass meine persönliche Unterredung mit Mr Elder hier vor einigen Monaten dieses neue wichtige Unternehmen<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">angeregt</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>hat, da die Linie der beabsichtigten Exploration Warburtons eine Diagonale ist, wird solche nur an einem Punkte diejenige von Giles schneiden u so bleiben beide Unternehmungen gegenseitig ungestört.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="de">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn1" n="2">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Petermann published<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>the text<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>from here to<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>immediately<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>before the valediction.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>Nun rüsten sich die Mess. John u Alex Forrest auch von Neuem, u ich habe Selbigen gerathen den Weg vom Murchison Fluss nach Sturts Creek einzuschlagen. Dadurch erlangen wir eine neue Diagonal Linie für die Geographie des westlichen Theils unseres Continents, während gleichzeitig der Weg eröffnet wird zu den reichen Basalt Weiden am Sturts Flusse, welche den berühmten Basaltic Downs Ostaustraliens (e.g. Peak Downs, Darlings Downs<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>&amp;c) so ähnlich sind. Auf der Forschungsreise Gregory's in den Jahren 1855 u 1856, in welcher ich ihn als Naturforscher begleitete, sahen wir das Ende dieser reichen Basaltländer nicht; u ich halte es nicht unwahrscheinlich, dass sie sich bis zur östlichen Basis der Gebirgszüge erstrecken, welche westlich die Flüsse De Gray u Fortescue in den Ocean senden.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="de">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In einem Jahre mag unter so günstigen Aussichten, zumal nach dem reichlichen Regen der letzten 2 oder 3 Jahre der grössere Theil des westlichen Innern der Geographie erschlossen sein.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="de">Stets Ihr</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="de">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="de">Ihren Hoheiten den Gothaer Prinzen sollen bei deren Hiersein von mir jede mir mögliche Aufmerksamkeit selbstverständlich erwiesen werden.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn2" n="3">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Petermann did not publish the postscript.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Melbourne Botanic Garden,</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">1 September 1872.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Since I wrote last, noble friend, Colonel Warburton has suddenly appeared on the scene to lead an exploring expedition from Central Mount Stuart<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn3" n="4">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>On the overland telegraph line, north of the MacDonnell Ranges, NT.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>to the Swan River,<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn4" n="5">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>WA.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>and this on the prompting and with the support of my friend, Senator<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Th. Elder.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn5" n="6">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Elder was a member of the SA Legislative Council at this time. The position did not carry the title ‘Senator’; M<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>may have<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>used this for the benefit of German readers in analogy with other bicameral systems such as that of the USA.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Yes, I believe, that my personal discussion here with Mr Elder a few months ago has<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">initiate</hi>
               </seg>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">d</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>this new important enterprise;<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>as the route of Warburton's planned exploration runs diagonally, it will cut across that of Giles<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn6" n="7">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ernest<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Giles was in the field attempting to reach tributaries of the Murchison River in WA<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(described in<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>E.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Giles (1875), pp. 5-68).</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>at only one point, and thus both enterprises remain independent of each other.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Messrs John and Alexander Forrest are also getting ready again, and I have suggested to them to make their way from the Murchison River to Sturt's Creek.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn7" n="8">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>WA.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>In this way we shall obtain a new diagonal line for the geography of the western part of our continent, while at the same time a route will be opened up to the rich basaltic grazing lands at Sturt's<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>River,<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn8" n="9">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>i.e. Sturt's</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Creek?</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>which are so similar to the famous basaltic<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>plains of eastern Australia (e.g. Peak Downs, Darling Downs,<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn9" n="10">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Qld.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>&amp;c.). During the exploring expedition of Gregory in the years 1855 and 1856,<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn10" n="11">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>North Australian Exploring Expedition, 1855-6.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>on which I accompanied him as naturalist, we did not see the end of these rich basaltic plains, and<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>I consider it not unlikely<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>that they extend as far as the eastern foothills of the mountain ranges<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>that<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>in<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>the west discharge the De Grey<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>River and the Fortescue River<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn11" n="12">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>WA.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>into the ocean.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Under such favourable prospects, and especially after the plentiful rains of the past two or three years,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>the greater part of the western interior should be opened up to geography in a year.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="margin-left: 1.75in; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Always your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="margin-left: 1.75in; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Their Highnesses the Princes of Gotha will, of course, be shown every attentiveness possible by<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>me during their stay here.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn12" n="13">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Prince Philip and Prince Augustus of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha visited Australia during October-November 1872.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>See<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Robin<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Brown<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(1986), p. 292.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
         </div>
      </body>
